T1  - Corporate Dividend Policies: Lessons from Private Firms
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhr108
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 25
IS  - 3
SP  - 711
EP  - 746
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We compare the dividend policies of publicly and privately held firms in order to help identify the forces shaping corporate dividends, and shed light on the behavior of privately held companies. We show that private firms smooth dividends significantly less than their public counterparts, suggesting that the scrutiny of public capital markets plays a central role in the propensity of firms to smooth dividends over time. Public firms pay relatively higher dividends that tend to be more sensitive to changes in investment opportunities than otherwise similar private firms. Ultimately, ownership structure and incentives play key roles in shaping dividend policies.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhr108
ER  - 



